node.text:
As a Black woman I know that we are expected to lift the nation to greet its better angels. If it took a village then, it’ll take a nation now. But until the tide turns it’ll take a nation of determined, smart, fearless Black women to defend our democracy and stay steady and true, despite the thunder and lightning. And I know we could talk about this all day. But I just want you to know that I’m with you. And we’ll need each other on the journey ahead. Everything we’ve learned to date will be tested. We must prevail. And we will. So stay encouraged and let’s link hands. We’ll need each other and we must find ways of coming together and combining our talent, our money and our agendas together. We must find groups to collaborate with, to turn a few into many, so we can make an impact. They are calling this the new dark ages, Well, good, we glow in the dark. And what is done in the dark comes to light. So glow. 

They cannot, they will not be successful if we work diligently. And although it may seem as if nothing’s changing, we know better. We are futurists, We’re used to looking past the chaos to see what really lies ahead. In the meantime, while they mine down under, and play catch up, we’ll source the sun for fuel and shoot for the moon. Like Congressman John Lewis on that bridge, we came prepared. node.text: Hello, I’m Erika Alexander and I’m an actress, writer, producer and director. I’m also cofounder of Color Farm Media (@colorfarm). I’ve played many parts over the years, but the one I cherish the most was the honor of being Hillary Clinton’s surrogate during, and in between, both of her presidential campaigns. In fact, I was told by Hillary that I was her most traveled surrogate. I’m sure that’s after President Clinton and Chelsea but that is a title I’ll always write on my heart. You see I love Hillary Rodham Clinton. I was a young woman when I first heard of her. I was attending the Philadelphia H. S. For Girls and I, we all, were advised and taught that strong women would be a source of inspiration and guidance for us as we moved along in our lives. I voted for her husband, President Bill Clinton for both his runs and I was fascinated with his no nonsense, feisty wife who seemed very much like the person I felt like inside. Turns out she was a Scorpio like me and she was interested in making the lives of women and children better, like me. It would be years before I would meet her. It happened when a friend, Lalanya Masters, invited me  to attend an event. A conference of America’s mayors. Lalanya knew I was also an amateur photographer and I confided in her that I had written a small list down on a piece of paper of the people I wanted to take portraits of, Hillary Clinton was on that list. I attended the event, and got to take a picture with her, but not of her. And although I was disappointed I didn’t get to take my picture, I got something else a lot better. One of her staff and friends Minyon Moore invited me and Lalanya to do an event for then Senator Clinton for young female entrepreneurs of color. We did that event and I introduced Senator Clinton. After that introduction I came down off the stage and another person, Darren Peters, complimented me and asked me if I wanted to be a surrogate. I replied, sure, then I took a beat and asked him, “What’s a surrogate?” And I was on my way! So here I am now on Secretary Hillary Rodham’s Instagram page talking to you. She’s given me the keys today, and I’m able to tell you, her followers, my story.

node.text: Twenty-seven years ago today, Maya Angelou read her poem "On the Pulse of Morning" on the occasion of Bill's first inauguration. Chelsea and I wrote about how she reinvented herself through reading in "The Book of #GutsyWomen."

There is nothing more powerful than our shared voices calling for change and our shared efforts to make that change a reality. ⁣
⁣
Young activists like Julieta Martinez are proof of that. I was overjoyed to join her at yesterday's #GenerationEquality Forum to talk about what we each can do to tackle the urgent issues that face us, from inequality to climate change.⁣

node.text:
I’m in Paris for the #GenerationEquality forum, the largest gathering of advocates for gender equality since the Fourth World Conference on Women in Beijing in 1995.⁣
 ⁣
My message for the activists and world leaders here—and for anyone who wants to create a better and more equal world—is that it’s no longer enough to talk about women’s rights.⁣
 ⁣
Rights are important, but they are nothing without the power to claim them. And we know that when women have the power to raise our voices, assert our rights, and rebuild economies, everyone will be better off.⁣
 ⁣
The data is there. When women are healthier and more economically secure, it lifts up families, communities, and entire nations. Repairing the damage the pandemic has wrought for women would result in $13 trillion in global GDP gains by 2030, according to one estimate. When women are included at the peace table, agreements are more likely to be reached and held to. ⁣
 ⁣
On the other side of the coin, we know that the rise of authoritarianism is inextricably linked to male privilege and supremacy. As Vice President Harris once said, the status of women is the status of democracy.⁣
 ⁣
In other words: The world has never needed gender equality more. It’s up to us to demand it.⁣
 ⁣
That means tackling the hurdles that still hold women back, including gender-based violence and abuse. It means treating reproductive rights, paid leave, affordable child care, and equal pay as the urgent priorities they are.⁣
 ⁣
We can work to expand women’s representation and leadership in every sphere, including the private sector. We can vote for women, and challenge deeply-entrenched ideas about what a leader looks like. We can call out sexism, racism, and discrimination against LGBTQ people in our culture, workplaces, and homes. And we can invest in organizations that advocate for women—work that is proven to advance not only women’s rights, but economic security and democracy too.⁣
 ⁣
Beijing was a watershed moment. Today, we stand at another. Let’s meet this moment not with tired ideas and incremental steps, but with the boldness, leadership, and resources needed to transform our world. #ActForEqual⁣
 ⁣
Photo: Doug Mills, AP
